ğŸŒ 4. Pods are running but traffic is not reaching
Validate the chain:

kubectl get svc
kubectl get endpoints
kubectl get ingress

Check:

Does service have endpoints?
Do endpoints match pod IPs?
Does ingress point to correct service and port?

EKS specific:

Node security group allows traffic from load balancer
NodePort range allowed
Load balancer health check path is correct
Target group shows healthy targets

ğŸ‘‰ Very common mistake
 Service port â‰  containerPort

ğŸ§± 5. Service works inside cluster but not outside
Test inside cluster:

kubectl run test --image=busybox -it --rm -- sh
wget http://<service-name>:<port>
If it works internally:
Check ingress annotations
Check LB listeners
Check security groups
Check target group health

ğŸ§­ 6. DNS problems inside EKS

Symptoms:

Services cannot resolve each other
External DNS fails

Checks:

kubectl get pods -n kube-system
kubectl logs -n kube-system deployment/coredns

Common causes:

CoreDNS pods not running
Node-to-node traffic blocked
NetworkPolicy blocking DNS

ğŸ•¸ï¸ 7. Pod-to-Pod networking failures

Important EKS fact:
 Pods receive IPs from VPC CIDR.

Check:
Subnet IP exhaustion
VPC CNI health
Security groups
Network policies

kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep aws-node
